<div id="review_555513709" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/555513709" />
    <a title="shereads" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4067659-shereads"><img alt="shereads" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1357230835p2/4067659.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/555513709?book_show_action=true">Mar 08, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="shereads" class="user" itemprop="url" name="shereads" href="/user/show/4067659-shereads">shereads</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer555513709" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3217856474649652565">I felt like book was trying to be too much at once and as a result, it was not as successful as it could have been as a fictional STORY or a well-being/self-help book. <br/><br/>I began with the impression that this would be some historical fiction/history re-write and in some ways it is. I particularly enjoy how each chapter is an answer to a question - very parable-like, and it takes a narrative tone that the Bible has in many instances. However, there are no real characters that carry over chapter to c</span>
  <span id="freeText3217856474649652565" style="display:none">I felt like book was trying to be too much at once and as a result, it was not as successful as it could have been as a fictional STORY or a well-being/self-help book. <br /><br />I began with the impression that this would be some historical fiction/history re-write and in some ways it is. I particularly enjoy how each chapter is an answer to a question - very parable-like, and it takes a narrative tone that the Bible has in many instances. However, there are no real characters that carry over chapter to chapter, who we get know, and who develop in some way. It is just a narrator dispensing life advice and wisdom to a crowd. If I had known this book was going to be some Socratic/Jesus mash-up, I may have been less disappointed - but about as equally impressed (which is not much). <br /><br />As a work of non-fiction, well-being, or modern day pseudo-political philosophy book; it's rather disorganized, not very clear, and gratuitous with the examples (too many 'stories' that actually dilute the lesson rather than make it stronger). <br /><br />To me, this book is having an identity crisis. It has redeeming qualities: some genuinely thought provoking concepts and ideas - but none that haven't been discussed before in a more effective medium or narrative voice.<br /><br />1.5/5</span>
  <a data-text-id="3217856474649652565" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


